---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Home" description="A personal photo archive for Famly-using households. bairn pulls your kid's photos and videos from the nursery feed onto your own disk with the post body, the educator's name, and the date embedded into each file via EXIF and XMP — so your child's history doesn't depend on Famly continuing to exist as a company.">
  <header class="hero">
    <img class="hero-glyph" src="/album-glyph.svg" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
    <p class="page-eyebrow">photo archive · cli</p>
    <h1 class="hero-title">bairn</h1>
    <p class="hero-lede">
      Photos and videos from your kid's daycare, kept on
      <em>your</em> disk, in a form that outlives the vendor.
    </p>
    <p class="hero-tagline">collected moments of early learning.</p>
    <div class="hero-cta">
      <a class="cta-primary" href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn">Read on GitLab →</a>
      <a class="cta-secondary" href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn/-/releases">Releases</a>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">What this is</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      Your daycare uses Famly. Every week the educators post a stream
      of photos and short videos of your kid: lunch, the sand pit, a
      collage they made on Wednesday, the moment they tried a new
      word. Famly is built for the in-the-moment surfacing of that
      stream. It is not built to be a long-term archive of your
      child's first years.
    </p>
    <p class="section-prose">
      <code>bairn</code> is a single Go binary that you run on your
      own machine, against your own household, with your own login.
      It pulls every photo and video the educators have posted,
      writes them into date-organized folders on your disk, and
      embeds the caption, the educator's name, the kid tags, and the
      date into each file's own EXIF and XMP metadata. Any photo
      viewer or future archival workflow can read those fields —
      today, and in twenty years.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">The vendor survives</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      The reason this matters is that an in-app feed is a handle to
      a service, not an artifact. When the company changes its mind
      about retention, sells to a different parent, deprecates the
      mobile app, or simply goes away, what you remember of your
      child's first three years of childcare goes with it.
    </p>
    <figure class="diagram">
      <img src="/vendor-survives.svg" alt="Flow diagram: Famly's nursery feed flows into bairn, which writes to your disk. Outages, account closures, and API changes originate at Famly but terminate at a barrier between bairn and the disk — the on-disk archive is unaffected." />
      <p class="diagram-caption">disruption stops at the disk boundary</p>
    </figure>
    <p class="section-prose">
      Once the bytes are on your disk with metadata embedded, none
      of those vendor outcomes touches the history. The file is the
      artifact, not a handle to a service.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">How <code>bairn</code> is shaped</h2>
    <div class="tile-grid">
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">flow · in</p>
        <p class="tile-headline">feed pages</p>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Famly's parent-side GraphQL surface, walked one page at a
          time at the rate a single human user would naturally
          generate. Schema introspected from the live endpoint, types
          codegen'd, response shapes pinned by a drift baseline.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">graphql · typed · introspected</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">discipline · posture</p>
        <p class="tile-headline">personal</p>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          One household, one operator, one set of credentials. No
          aggregation across families, no telemetry, no shared
          identifiers, no third-party calls. The binary doesn't know
          there is more than one of you.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">one household · rate-limited</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">flow · out</p>
        <p class="tile-headline">files</p>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          JPEG and MP4 written to dated folders on your disk, with
          the caption, the educator's name, the kid tags, and the
          date embedded as EXIF and XMP. Optionally pushed into
          Immich after the on-disk write; the disk copy is always
          the source of truth.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">disk first · immich optional</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">discipline · lifetime</p>
        <p class="tile-headline">archival</p>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          The file is the artifact, not a handle to a service. Open
          formats, standard metadata, no proprietary container.
          Readable in any year by any tool that has ever read a JPEG.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">exif/xmp · open format · any year</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">Why Famly</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      Vendors fall along a spectrum when an outside party builds
      against their surface. The <em>hostile</em> ones forbid access
      in their terms and chase violations. The <em>silent</em> ones
      forbid access but ignore violations and tolerate the drift. A
      third group — the <em>engaged</em> ones — restricts usage in
      their terms, acknowledges the use case in support interactions,
      and points users toward self-service solutions. Famly is in
      that third group, and that's what makes <code>bairn</code>
      possible: the surface is inspectable, the schema is
      introspectable, and the vendor's response when asked about
      export was to decline gracefully and point at the surface they
      already publish.
    </p>
    <p class="section-prose">
      This isn't a license — it's reputational, and the reciprocal
      obligation is to stay careful: one household, one operator, the
      rate a human generates, no aggregation, no resale, no agent
      farm. See <a href="https://andrew.dunn.dev/writing/progressive-vendor-stance/">a
      progressive vendor stance for the agent-native future</a> for
      the longer argument.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">Install</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      Three ways to run <code>bairn</code>, in increasing order of
      isolation from your day-to-day machine. Each release ships
      cosign-signed binaries, a CycloneDX SBOM per architecture, and
      a SLSA v1.0 provenance attestation, all verifiable against
      GitLab's OIDC issuer.
    </p>
    <div class="tile-list">
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">option a</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">Go install</h3>
        <pre>go install gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn/cmd/bairn@latest</pre>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Build from source against your local Go toolchain. Best
          for contributors and anyone who already runs Go for other
          work. No signature verification — trust comes from the
          module proxy.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">go 1.25+ · module-cached</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">option b</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">Prebuilt binary</h3>
        <pre>curl -L -o bairn https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn/-/releases/permalink/latest/downloads/bairn-linux-amd64
chmod +x bairn</pre>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          Cosign-signed binary from the
          <a href="https://gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn/-/releases">releases page</a>
          — pair the download with the matching <code>.sig</code>
          and verify against the GitLab OIDC issuer before running.
          The hardened option that doesn't ask you to install a
          toolchain.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">linux/amd64 · linux/arm64 · darwin/arm64 · cosign</p>
      </div>
      <div class="tile">
        <p class="tile-eyebrow">option c</p>
        <h3 class="tile-headline">Container image</h3>
        <pre>podman pull registry.gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn/cli:latest
podman run --rm \
  -v "$PWD/archive:/archive" \
  -v "$PWD/config.toml:/config.toml:ro" \
  registry.gitlab.com/dunn.dev/bairn/cli:latest \
  --config /config.toml --out /archive</pre>
        <p class="tile-prose">
          The OCI image is the prebuilt binary copied into a thin
          runtime layer; the binary inside the image is the same
          cosign-signed artifact as option B (byte-for-byte). Best
          for cron on a homelab box where you don't want Go or a
          random binary on disk. The image itself is cosign-signed
          by digest.
        </p>
        <p class="tile-meta">oci · cosign-signed-by-digest · rootless-ok</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">Who this is for</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      A parent, co-parent, or household admin whose kid's daycare
      uses Famly and who wants a permanent local copy of every photo
      and video the educators post, with metadata that survives any
      future tooling change.
    </p>
    <p class="section-prose">
      If your school doesn't use Famly, or if you're happy enough
      with how the mobile app surfaces history, <code>bairn</code>
      is not for you. It's also not multi-tenant — one binary, one
      household, one disk.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-title">What this isn't</h2>
    <p class="section-prose">
      Not a privacy gateway. Every piece of context the vendor
      exposes lands inside the file you keep — that's the whole
      point of EXIF and XMP for archival. What happens to those
      files after you have them is your call. Not a scraping service
      either: one operator, the rate of one human, written to feel
      like a parent backing up their own photos because that's what
      it is.
    </p>
  </section>
</Layout>
